result.execSummary:
All charges against James Francis Jr in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. James Francis Jr is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:15 p.m.  Defendant James Francis in court, in custody.  Matthew J Tingstad appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Complaint filed, copy given to def with rt to atty info.  Def waives reading of complaint out loud.  Court summarizes charges.  Record reflects we are dealing with older laws since changes made in 1999.  DA:  Vic rts complied with.  Court:  Explains bond meaning to def.  DA:  Has reviewed similar cases and bonds and requests $50,000 cash.  Perhaps house arrest option.  Concern is protecting victim.  Asks no contact with victim or family of victim.  Victim makes statement.  Court asks def for any response.  He responds he lives two blocks away and cannot afford $50,000.00 bail.  DA asks for no contact w/anyone under 18 if def is on house arrest.  Court:  Due to nature of crime, Court accepts DA recommendation of $50,000 cash.  Def may ask for reduction later.  No contact w/victim by himself or and by any third party.  No contact with anyone under 18 unless w/parent.  Set for IA on 4/11 at 9:00 a.m.  Atty may file any motions at that time.
